<paper id="1951707894"><title>Flexible Access Control with Master Keys</title><year>1989</year><authors><author org="Queen's University at Kingston" id="2283491954">Gerald C. Chick</author><author org="Queen's University at Kingston" id="2228390319">Stafford E. Tavares</author></authors><n_citation>113</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1591932736</reference><reference>1840081982</reference><reference>1971192353</reference><reference>1976767440</reference><reference>1985063853</reference><reference>1996360405</reference><reference>2000862610</reference><reference>2012168171</reference><reference>2031338211</reference><reference>2042334369</reference><reference>2159401786</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/0-387-34805-0_29</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.59252">Key management</keyword><keyword weight="0.57072">Key space</keyword><keyword weight="0.48113">Hierarchical control system</keyword><keyword weight="0.58819">Key generation</keyword><keyword weight="0.47623">Authentication</keyword><keyword weight="0.43897">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.44948">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.44824">Computer network</keyword><keyword weight="0.48007">Digital signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.4319">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.51941">Access control</keyword><keyword weight="0.58654">Key distribution center</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer-Verlag</publisher><abstract>We show how to create a master key scheme for controlling access to a set of services. Each master key is a concise representation for a list of service keys, such that only service keys in this list can be computed easily from the master key. Our scheme is more flexible than others, permitting hierarchical organization and expansion of the set of services.</abstract></paper>